    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm studying for my structural mechanics exam. can u explain why we actually need to add steel rebar to concrete foundations? like why isnt the concrete itself enough to handle the loads? im a bit confused about the relationship between compressive and tensile strength here.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Concrete is incredibly strong in compression, which is why it can bear heavy loads like building foundations, but it is very weak in tension. When a foundation bends under load, the top part compresses while the bottom part tries to stretch, creating tensile forces that pure concrete simply cannot handle. Adding steel rebar provides the necessary tensile strength because steel is much stronger than concrete when pulled, allowing the composite material to resist both compression and tension. Without the rebar, the foundation would crack and fail under bending moments, even if the concrete itself is of high quality. This combination creates a structural system that is far more robust than using either material alone.",
      "source": "target",
