    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so it's basically a partnership between the two materials. what happens inside the slab though, like if there's a huge sudden load, does the tension happen instantly throughout the whole thing? how do the forces actually distribute themselves through the internal structure of the concrete?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The forces do not distribute instantly throughout the whole slab; instead, the load travels through the concrete until it reaches the critical section where bending moments are highest. At that specific point, the internal structure creates a neutral axis where stress is zero, while the bottom fibers immediately begin to stretch and develop tensile stress as soon as the load exceeds the concrete's limit. This stress concentrates right at the weakest point in the span, which is why rebar is strategically placed in the tension zone to catch the failure before it spreads. The concrete carries the compression on top, while the steel takes the tension at the bottom, working together to prevent the slab from snapping due to localized stress concentrations.",
